This lab demonstrates how to implement NAT (Network Address Translation) in a small office environment.
We will see how private IP addresses are translated into a public IP, allowing internal devices to communicate with a server representing the Internet.

Devices Used:
Router 2911	1	NAT router, connects LAN to WAN
Switch 2960	1	Connects PCs to Router
PC 3	Internal office devices (private IPs)
Server 1 Public server (represents Internet)

PCs: LAN (192.168.10.x / 255.255.255.0)
Router G0/0: LAN interface (inside NAT)
Router G0/1: WAN interface (outside NAT, public IP)
Server: Public network (200.10.10.10 / 255.255.255.0)

LAN
PC1	192.168.10.11	255.255.255.0	192.168.10.1 <- GATEWAY
PC2	192.168.10.12	255.255.255.0	192.168.10.1 <- GATEWAY
PC3	192.168.10.13	255.255.255.0	192.168.10.1 <- GATEWAY
Router G0/0	192.168.10.1	255.255.255.0	-

WAN
Router G0/1	200.10.10.2	255.255.255.0
Server	200.10.10.10	255.255.255.0

ROUTER CLI
Router(config)# interface g0/0
Router(config-if)# ip address 192.168.10.1 255.255.255.0   ! Assign LAN IP
Router(config-if)# no shutdown                                  ! Activate interface
Router(config-if)# ip nat inside                                   ! Mark as NAT inside
Router(config-if)# exit

Router(config)# interface g0/1
Router(config-if)# ip address 200.10.10.2 255.255.255.0      ! Assign public IP
Router(config-if)# no shutdown                                  ! Activate interface
Router(config-if)# ip nat outside                                  ! Mark as NAT outside
Router(config-if)# exit

Router(config)# access-list 1 permit 192.168.10.0 0.0.0.255   ! Allow LAN subnet for NAT       
Router(config)# ip nat inside source list 1 interface g0/1 overload   ! Map all private IPs to single public IP

Router# show ip nat translations
(Image1)
Pro ->	Protocol (ICMP, TCP, UDP)
Inside Global ->	The public IP (and port/ICMP ID) seen by the outside network
Inside Local ->	The private IP (and port/ICMP ID) of the internal PC
Outside Local ->	IP/port of the server as the router sees it (same as Outside Global for this lab)
Outside Global ->	The actual IP/port of the server on the public network

How it works?
Router maps Inside Local → Inside Global (private → public IP)
When a reply comes from the server, router uses port/ICMP ID to know which PC to forward it to
Multiple PCs can share the same public IP using different ports / ICMP IDs

Only active translations appear in NAT table. If a PC does not send traffic, it will not be listed.
NAT/PAT allows multiple internal devices to share one public IP.
ICMP uses sequence numbers/IDs instead of TCP/UDP ports.                                                              
       
